 mid-1960s workers have joined organized labor to a much greater extent. Given that the two countries are outwardly so similar, what explains this paradox? This book provides a detailed comparative analysis of both countries using, among other things, a detailed survey conducted in the United States and Canada by the Ipsos-Reid polling group.The authors explain that the relative reluctance of employees in the United States to join unions, compared with those in Canada, is rooted less in their attitudes toward unions than in the former country's deep-seated tradition of individualism and laissez-faire economic values. Canada has a more statist, social democratic tradition, which is in turn attributable to its Tory and European conservative lineage. Canadian values are therefore more supportive of unionism, making unions more powerful and thus, paradoxically, lowering public approval of unions. Public approval is higher in the United States, where unions exert less of an influence over politics and the economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLabor union memberszCanada. 0aLabor union memberszUnited States. 0aLabor unionszCanada. 0aLabor unionszUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLabor History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aunion approval, trade union organization, organized labor, america and canada, political science and sociology.1 aGomez, Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatchanovski, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKochan, Thomas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeltz, Noah M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740